## Goal
Implement the chained apply slices for `module-2-application-flow` through the real public intake flow and finish the minimum safe legacy-Atlas compatibility remediation.

## Instructions
- Keep technical artifacts in English.
- Respect the current Spanish-only runtime and legacy `/en/...` redirect behavior.
- Deliver reviewable increments only: PR 1 foundation/persistence, PR 2 public intake, PR 3 admin operations.
- Do not expand public intake into admin UI, auth, email, or reporting.
- Keep this continuation scoped to the minimum safe compatibility remediation for legacy Atlas data on reads and writes.

## Discoveries
- `pnpm` is not on PATH in this environment; project commands must run through `corepack pnpm`.
- The existing repo already follows a pure TypeScript validator pattern in `src/validators/program.ts`, so the new application domain can stay consistent without adding a schema validation library.
- Deferring the `MONGODB_URI` guard until connection time keeps build and static analysis green before runtime secrets are configured.
- Next.js `"use server"` modules can export only async functions, so shared cookie constants for the apply flow must live outside `actions.ts`.
- A short-lived httpOnly cookie cleanly gates `/apply/success` direct access while keeping the public slice server-first and localized.
- In Next.js server actions, `redirect()` throws, so status-action redirects must stay outside broad `try/catch` blocks or they will be treated as failures.
- The live `fp_pv_interculturas.applications` collection still contains legacy documents where `birthDate` is stored as a BSON Date, `identityDocument` can be null, `applicationType.code` remains `volunteering`, `applicationTypeHistory` can be empty, and `statusHistory` still uses `{from,to,reason,changedAt,changedBy}` entries.
- Repository-side normalization is the correct compatibility boundary: keep read parsing strict by normalizing legacy shapes before `parseApplication`, while leaving submission/update validation strict for new writes.
- `corepack pnpm dlx tsx` can execute source imports for Atlas-backed verification after sourcing `.env.local`, which makes service-level create/update checks feasible without adding a permanent test runner.
- Mongoose model caching can preserve an outdated nested schema across hot reloads; after a contract migration, `models.Application` must be explicitly dropped in non-production so `/es/apply` stops validating against the stale pre-legacy snapshot.
- Next.js server-action forms can be verified without a browser by replaying the rendered multipart POST contract, including the hidden `$ACTION_*` inputs emitted in the HTML.
- Atlas database names are capped at 38 bytes, so isolated empty-state runtimes need a short temporary database name when swapping `MONGODB_URI`.

